<%- include('partials/header') %>

<main id="main-content">
  <article>
    <h1>About Me: My Full Story</h1>

    <section aria-labelledby="early-tech">
      <h2 id="early-tech">How it started</h2>
      <p>
        I am Bassem Krayem. I was born as blind in 11 August 2004. My love for
        tech started when I bought my first smart phone, it was a Galaxy J2. I
        loved to explore everything, every setting in it. I remember I was
        breaking a lot of things and I don't know how to solve it so I format it
        lol. I remember that in one day I formatted it three times in one day—or
        let's say reset to factory settings format it, in 2015.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then in 2017 I bought my first laptop, it was a Dell. First I used it
        only to watch YouTube for 2 and half years, then later I discovered the
        world of audio games, the gaming world for blinds. In the end of 2019
        and the start of 2020 I started audio gaming. I remember I started with
        <em>The Killer</em> by
        <a href="https://blindmasters.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
          >blindmasters.org</a
        >
        lol—they are not running it any more, it's old now. Then I played the
        most popular online game among the blinds in all the world:
        <strong>STW (Survive the Wild)</strong> by
        <a href="https://samtupy.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
          >samtupy.com</a
        >
        lol. I keep playing until the year 2024 then he stop it. To be honest,
        all blind people who played it was angry from this decision.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="becoming-dev">
      <h2 id="becoming-dev">Deciding to be a Developer</h2>
      <p>
        In 2022 I started to be developer. I started to think that I need to
        know how these games are build, but later I said I can not earn money
        with audio games so I decided to be a web developer. I started to read
        the HTML tutorial in
        <a href="https://w3schools.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
          >w3schools.com</a
        >
        but I don't understand it a lot because they only have read-only.
      </p>
      <p>
        By coincidence I discovered the amazing, very amazing—what I say about
        this platform it's not enough—<strong>freeCodeCamp</strong>.
        <a href="https://freecodecamp.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
          >freecodecamp.org</a
        >
        It's the most accessible website, they considered blinds when they
        design their curriculum. So I learned Responsive Web Design from them.
        Yes I am blind true, but I was following them like "create a flex
        property" or "set the background color"—it's pure instructions I can
        follow. I learned HTML and CSS then I learned JS—not much but just a
        little bit.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="education-struggle">
      <h2 id="education-struggle">The School System & Bakaloria</h2>
      <p>
        I passed my bakaloria exam. I was in the literature section in the
        School Ennour for Blinds in Tunis Ben Arous. I wanted to be in
        Informatique but in that time when I was student in high school they
        don't allow us. But now the blinds can choose Informatique! Did you see?
        They are able to do but I wasn't able, cause by coincidence they meet
        the President of Tunisia and they told him about that problem and
        <strong>booooom</strong>, suddenly it become normal!
      </p>
      <p>
        Ok, let's move on in my story. After taking my bakaloria certificate I
        said ok let's try to study in software engineering in university. But it
        was hard cause in normal university they don't let us study just
        programming and coding concepts, but there is a lot of subjects like
        math, physics, and things like that so my blindness will not help. Then
        I decided to study English in the University of Literature in Manouba. I
        studied the first semester from October 2024 until Jan 2025.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="holberton-test">
      <h2 id="holberton-test">The Holberton Adventure</h2>
      <p>
        Then I discovered
        <a href="https://holbertonschool.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
          >Holberton School</a
        >
        in Jan 2024. I passed the admission test, it was composed from 3 phases.
        The first is to answer some questions to test your ability to search—I
        remember only the ENIAC computer something like that. The second phase,
        they give us a Linux server and we are required to do some actions like
        install Emacs editor then setup a static site via Apache.
      </p>
      <p>
        The third phase... lol I remembered a funny thing happened with me. I
        find a page telling me I have 30 minutes to finish, but where is the
        "Start" button Bassem? I spend a whole day to search! I posted in a
        forum, I thought my screen reader unable to locate it. Then the girl who
        told me about Holberton told me they will contact me about this stage
        lol. I was waiting, counting any minute for their call! Finally I got
        the call. I told them I am blind and they told me:
        <em
          >"No problem, if you reached this stage of the test then you are able
          to study with us."</em
        >
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="current-path">
      <h2 id="current-path">Specialization & Future</h2>
      <p>
        I started in February 5th 2024. We studied Linux, then C, then Python
        with JS and ES6 basics of TypeScript. After the first 9 months, I choose
        to study in the Fullstack Web specialization. I studied 3 months then I
        decided to stop taking a break to improve myself.
      </p>
      <p>
        I improved myself in Python by taking the
        <a
          href="https://www.datacamp.com/completed/statement-of-accomplishment/track/5be69eac6cd4b8bf4c3e3ceca658647d26068750"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          >Associate Python Developer</a
        >
        and I completed 61% of the
        <a
          href="https://app.datacamp.com/learn/career-tracks/python-programmer"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          >Python Developer Track</a
        >
        from
        <strong
          ><a href="https://datacamp.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
            >Data Camp</a
          ></strong
        >
        in this period, it was good course, and I studied the amazing
        <a
          href="https://www.udemy.com/course/nodejs-express-mongodb-bootcamp/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          >Node.js course by Jonas Schmedtmann</a
        >
        in
        <a href="https://udemy.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Udemy</a>.
        And I took some certifications from
        <strong
          ><a href="https://freecodecamp.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
            >freeCodeCamp</a
          ></strong
        >
        in that time:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a
            href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/certification/bassem_krayem/back-end-development-and-apis"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            >Back End Development and APIs Certification</a
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          <a
            href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/certification/bassem_krayem/relational-database-v8"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            >Relational Databases Certification</a
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          <a
            href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/certification/bassem_krayem/quality-assurance-v7"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            >Quality Assurance Certification</a
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Then I went back to study in Holberton after strengthening myself more,
        and here I am in April 21, 2026. I am building this website just now
        because it's in a project in Holberton School—they want us to build a
        website for ourselves. Whenever there are new things in my story, if I
        still have time in this life, I will write them in this page in the
        future,
        <strong>Inshallah</strong>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="how-built">
      <h2 id="how-built">How I built this website</h2>
      <p>
        In the GitHub Student Pack, there are free services gifted by them. I
        got the domain <strong>bassem-krayem.dev</strong> a year free from
        Name.com website and I host it in Heroku for free because the GitHub
        Student Pack as well.
      </p>
      <p>
        I have built it using Node.js and Express server-side rendered using the
        templating engine EJS. You are able to find the repo in my
        <a
          href="https://github.com/bassem-krayem/bassem-krayem-website"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          >GitHub</a
        >
        of this project if you want to take look in the simple code of it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="skills-tech">
      <h2 id="skills-tech">Technical Skills & Technologies</h2>
      <p>
        In my journey through Holberton and self-study, I have mastered these
        tools:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Languages:</strong> Python, Node.js (JavaScript/ES6), Bash
          Scripting, Basics of TypeScript.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Databases & DBMS:</strong> MongoDB with Mongoose, PostgreSQL
          (PSQL), and MySQL.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Frameworks & Tools:</strong> Express.js, simple knowledge with
          Flask, Linux (Ubuntu), Git, and GitHub.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Specialties:</strong> Backend Architecture, RESTful APIs, and
          Accessibility (A11y).
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="human-languages">
      <h2 id="human-languages">Languages I Speak</h2>
      <p>
        I am a bilingual engineer: <strong>Arabic</strong> (Native) and
        <strong>English</strong> (Intermediate).
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="hobbies">
      <h2 id="hobbies">Beyond the Code</h2>
      <p>When I am not sitting in front of my laptop, I am usually:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Reading:</strong> I have a deep passion for novels. I love
          exploring electronic books through the <strong>Abjad app</strong>, the
          <strong>Motamayezoon library</strong>, or various Telegram channels. I
          also enjoy following stories on <strong>Wattpad</strong>. Reading is
          my way of traveling the world through my imagination.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Sports:</strong> I love doing sport exercises. It keeps my
          mind sharp and my body active after long hours of coding.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Audio Gaming:</strong> Though I spend less time on it now, I
          still enjoy the community and the challenge of well-designed audio
          games.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</main>

<%- include('partials/footer') %>
